{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9770,"record_hash":"sha256:4fa861d716d963275b1554b692272af6d054b42345c2eb387c3b6243e44a2d4d","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:30:11.616Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 7af10d\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1012\nOutput:\n## Primitive Access Patterns\n\nThe model should make these reads efficient.\n\nDefine the primitive read surface independently of product UX:\n\n- `listSessions(project, max_sessions?)`: discovers recent sessions; richer\n  filters and cursors can be added in a feature/API layer when needed\n- `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`: returns turn summaries plus\n  hydrated records for a bounded timeline window\n- `findRelatedSessions(target)`: returns verified session candidates with\n  matching turn keys for a branch/review/change target\n- `getRelatedSessionDetail(target, session_key, turn_window)`:\n  hydrates records around highlighted turns\n\nKeep those as read facades, not storage objects. They can evolve without\nrewriting turn metadata, and product-specific surfaces can compose them later.\n\nFor a handoff-style consumer:\n\n1. read the project session index\n2. choose a session by recency, explicit selection, or relationship\n3. read session metadata, turns, and transcript records\n4. render records grouped by turn, or choose a recent turn window\n5. include environment snapshots only when useful for re-orientation\n\nFor a review-style consumer:\n\n1. start from a branch, change, or PR\n2. use derived lookup indexes to find candidate turns and sessions\n3. resolve project-scoped sessions for those candidates\n4. read turns and observations for those sessions\n5. rank and explain the likely relationship from the underlying observations\n6. render the underlying transcript records for the selected windows\n\nFor a GitButler worktree with multiple applied branches, review sharing should\nbe able to show the whole associated session while highlighting the likely\nturns for the selected branch or PR. A narrower turn window can be selected\nlater without changing the session as the durable object.\n\nThe review product must not depend on a naive scan over all sessions and turns,\neven for the POC. The expected product query is:\n\n```te\n[TRUNCATED]\nssions?\n```\n\nThat query needs an index-first read path. The system can still avoid persisted\nassociations as durable truth, but capture should write enough derived lookup\nentries to make branch/PR review lookup cheap.\n\nA useful split:\n\n- **observations:** persisted source of truth, including transcript records,\n  capture turns, and environment snapshots\n- **derived lookup indexes:** persisted materialized views for fast candidate\n  discovery, safe to rebuild when heuristics change\n- **association result:** computed on read from candidates plus observations,\n  with highlighted turn keys and heuristic/schema version\n\nThis means association work is split across write and read time:\n\n- **Capture time:** write observations and deterministic index memberships from\n  the current capture turn snapshot, such as observed branch names, review ids,\n  and change ids.\n- **Read time:** answer association questions by looking up candidate turns from\n  indexes, reading their observations, and scoring/explaining likely related\n  sessions with the current heuristic version.\n\nCapture should not write final inferred relationships such as \"this PR is\nassociated with this session\" or \"this branch was produced by this session.\"\nIt only writes the facts and lookup entries needed to answer those questions\nefficiently later.\n\nThe index is not the association. It is a disposable acceleration structure.\nIf the heuristic changes, a future namespace or rebuild can let old sessions\nbenefit retroactively.\n\nFor v1, write only branch, review, and change indexes:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:<target-key-hash> = set<IndexHit JSON string>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:<target-key-hash> = set<IndexHit JSON string>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:change:<target-key-hash> = set<IndexHit JSON string>\n```\n\nThe index value includes both the session key and turn key so an index lookup can\nresolve directly to the owning session without scanning session turn lists. Use\na compact JSON string value rather than a custom delimiter:\n\n```json\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:30:11.616Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}